[[File:640x320 Ali Darass.jpg|thumb|Ali Darassa]]
'''Ali Darassa Mahamat''' (born 23 July 1965), also known as '''Ali Nassaraza Darassa''', '''Ali Daras''', and '''Ali Ndarass''' is Nigerian leader of the [[Central African Republic|Central African]] rebel group, the Union for Peace in the Central African Republic (UPC), which is dominant around [[Bambari]].<ref name=fp1015>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/10/28/one-day-we-will-start-a-big-war-central-african-republic-un-violence/|title=One day we will start a big war|publisher=Foreign Policy|accessdate=13 February 2017}}</ref> He is an ethnic [[Fula people|Fula]]<ref>In {{lang-fr|link=no|Peul}}. In {{lang-ff|Pullo}} (pl. ''Fulɓe'').</ref> and his UPC is largely Fula. Darassa was the right-hand man of Chadian rebel leader, [[Abdel Kader Baba-Laddé]] until Baba-Laddé abandoned his armed struggle in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|language=French|title=Blog of the storytellers|url=http://thibautribar.blogspot.my/2015/10/ali-darassa-mahamat-est-un-chef-rebelle.html|publisher=tribautribarblogspot|date=27 October 2015}}</ref> The UPC is an Ex-seleka faction made up of disbanded members of the former rebel coalition known as [[Seleka]]. Starting in November 2016, another Ex-seleka faction, the FPRC, allied with their former enemy, the Anti-balaka, and attacked UPC.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2017/02/16/central-african-republic-executions-rebel-group|title=Central African Republic: Executions by rebel group|publisher=Human Rights Watch|accessdate=17 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=newsweek0217>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/central-african-republic-war-fprc-car-556068|title=U.N. ‘KILLS REBEL COMMANDER’ IN CENTRAL AFRICAN REPUBLIC AIRSTRIKES|publisher=|accessdate=14 February 2017}}</ref> The fighting displaced 20,000 and was ethnic in nature with the FPRC singling out [[Fulani people]].<ref name=reuters0217>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-centralafrica-violence-idUSKBN15R0WC|title=U.N. air strikes in Central African Republic kill several: militia|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=14 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=newsweek0217/> He is reportedly well studied in past UN peacekeeping missions in order to deal with the peacekeeping mission known as [[MINUSCA]] in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-38967461|title=Peacekeeping, African warlords and Donald Trump|publisher=BBC news|accessdate=25 February 2017}}</ref>

