{{about|Mary Parker n&eacute;e Ayer|other people|Mary Parker (disambiguation)}}
{{Infobox person | name = Mary Parker | image = | caption = | birth_name = Mary Ayer | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date|1692|9|22}} | death_place = [[Salem Village]], [[Province of Massachusetts Bay]] | death_cause = [[Execution]] by [[hanging]] | residence = | nationality = [[English people|English]] | known_for = Convicted of witchcraft in the [[Salem witch trials]] | occupation = | spouse = | children = | parents = }}
'''Mary (née Ayer) Parker''' of [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover, Massachusetts Bay Colony]], the daughter of [[John Ayer]],<ref>Anderson, R.C., Reitwiesner, W.A., Roberts, G.B. (1977) "The Matrilinear Line of President Ford" ''[[The American Genealogist]]'' 53:56</ref> was executed by hanging on September 22, 1692, with several [[Alice Parker (Salem)|others]], for witchcraft in the [[Salem witch trials]]. She was 55 years old and a widow. Mary's husband, Nathan, died in 1685.<ref name="Kelly">Kelly, Jacqueline "[http://salem.lib.virginia.edu/people?group.num=all&mbio.num=mb42 The Untold Story of Mary Ayer Parker: Gossip and Confusion in 1692.]" Revised for presentation at the Berkshire Conference. June 2005.</ref> [[Nicholas Noyes]] officiated. Her daughter, Sarah Parker, was also accused.<ref name="Kelly"/><ref>Robinson, Enders A. "Salem Witchcraft and Hawthorne's House of Seven Gables", pp. 251-55. Bowie, Md.: Heritage Books. 1992.<!-- ISBN needed --></ref>
Parker was an 8th great-grandmother of [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[George W. Bush]], who is a descendant or relative of up to 217{{how|date=October 2015}} of the trials' participants.{{Citation needed|date=December 2013}}
