[[File:Ventura Blanco Encalada (2).jpg|thumb|Ventura Blanco Encalada (2)]]
'''Ventura Blanco y Calvo de Encalada''' (c. 1782 – June 19, 1856) was a [[Chile]]an [[political figure]]. 

Blanco Encalada was born in [[Sucre|Chuquisaca]], [[Bolivia]], the son of Manuel Lorenzo Blanco Cicerón and of Mercedes Calvo de Encalada y Recabarren (a Spanish father and a Chilean mother). He was trained for the Army in [[Spain]], where he became a ''Guard de Corps'' and a lieutenant in the ''Regimiento de Dragones de Sangunto''.  During the [[Peninsular War]], he supported [[Joseph Bonaparte]] and eventually was forced to emigrate to [[France]]. He returned to Buenos Aires in 1816, and moved to Chile in 1820, where his younger brother [[Manuel Blanco Encalada|Manuel]] was an important political figure who went on to become its [[President of Chile|first President]].

In 1826, President [[Ramón Freire]] named him [[Ministry of the Interior (Chile)#Ministers of Government and Foreign Affairs|Minister of Government and Foreign Affairs]] and in 1827,  Vice President [[Francisco Antonio Pinto]] named him [[Ministry of Finance of Chile|Secretary of Treasury]]. After the defeat of the liberals in the [[Chilean Civil War of 1829]], he retired from politics. Blanco Encalada spent his last years teaching at the [[Universidad de Chile]], where he became [[Dean (education)|Dean]] of the School of Humanities.

